><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q55 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">John Stevenson:</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> Why should</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">n’t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> we just move to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the point where all business rates growth is retained?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Brandon Lewis</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">: There is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">a pretty simple </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">answer to that, which is that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">that has an impact on public e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">xpenditure</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, and it is unrealistic to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">think that central Government and the Treasury are not going to want to make sure that we have a grip </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">on that kind of expenditure.  To see it move</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> much beyond where it is now in the near future, while </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">we are where we are economically—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</s